 the parsing can be validated at Unit level with realistic mock data, making Integration sufficient for full behavior verification. are most likely since the tool parses git output rather than reading files directly. So **Unit** testing with mock diff output showing binary file lines should catch the actual failure modes.\n\nLet me finalize the test levels: Renamed files need real git operations, so **System**. Binary files can be caught at **Unit** level by mocking the diff output. Empty repos require actual git subprocess behavior, making that **System**. Matching counts and staged versus unstaged changes both depend on real git history and state, so those are **System** as well. For renamed files, the most likely real production failure stems from either git being called without proper rename detection flags or the tool misinterpreting actual git output. This points to System level testing as the minimum needed.\n\nWhen assigning confidence across test levels, I should consider what would actually catch failures in production. Unit tests with mocked git output might miss subprocess issues, so they're less likely to be sufficient. System level testing with real git subprocess calls would reliably catch whether rename detection works end-to-end.\n\nFor binary files, the parsing logic itself could be validated at Unit level with mock data, but Integration level becomes more likely since real binary files in a real repository would expose actual edge cases. System testing adds less marginal value here.\n\nEmpty repositories present a similar pattern—mocking git commands at Unit level misses real behavior, while System level with an actual empty git repository would catch genuine failures.\n\nFor count matching, Unit testing can't validate against real history, so System level with actual git history becomes the most critical. Integration testing with real files but mocked git output falls short of catching the actual counting logic against real data.\n\nStaged versus